The potential for integer overflow still exists in the calculation before the check. When computing maxPoints = cols * rows where both are Long values, if the multiplication result exceeds Long.MAX_VALUE, it will overflow. The check 'maxPoints > Int.MAX_VALUE / 2' only guards against allocating too large an array, but doesn't prevent the overflow in the multiplication itself. Consider adding overflow detection before the multiplication or using checked arithmetic.
```suggestion
        val maxPoints = try {
            Math.multiplyExact(cols, rows)
        } catch (e: ArithmeticException) {
            // Overflow in multiplication indicates an unreasonably large primitive count.
            // Bail out to avoid using a corrupted maxPoints value and prevent OOM.
            return
        }
