The recursive directory scanning function lacks protection against infinite recursion that could occur with symbolic links or circular directory structures. This could cause a stack overflow. Consider adding a maximum depth limit or tracking visited paths to prevent infinite recursion.
```suggestion
        // Entry point: delegate to the internal helper with recursion safeguards
        return scanRemoteFilesRecursively(
            provider = provider,
            currentRemotePath = currentRemotePath,
            currentRelativePath = currentRelativePath,
            depth = 0,
            visitedPaths = mutableSetOf()
        )
    }

    private suspend fun scanRemoteFilesRecursively(
        provider: RemoteStorageProvider,
        currentRemotePath: String,
        currentRelativePath: String,
        depth: Int,
        visitedPaths: MutableSet<String>,
    ): List<RemoteFileWithRelativePath> {
        val results = mutableListOf<RemoteFileWithRelativePath>()

        // Prevent infinite recursion due to cycles or excessively deep directory structures
        val maxDepth = 64
        if (depth > maxDepth) {
            Logger.w("SyncManager", "Max directory recursion depth ($maxDepth) exceeded at $currentRemotePath")
            return results
        }

        // Skip already visited paths to avoid cycles in the directory graph
        if (!visitedPaths.add(currentRemotePath)) {
            Logger.w("SyncManager", "Detected cycle while scanning, skipping already visited path: $currentRemotePath")
            return results
        }

        try {
            val items = provider.listFiles(currentRemotePath)
            for (item in items) {
                // Ensure proper path separation
                val itemRelativePath =
                    if (currentRelativePath.isEmpty()) item.name else "$currentRelativePath/${item.name}"

                if (item.isDirectory) {
                    val childRemotePath = "$currentRemotePath/${item.name}"
                    results.addAll(
                        scanRemoteFilesRecursively(
                            provider = provider,
                            currentRemotePath = childRemotePath,
                            currentRelativePath = itemRelativePath,
                            depth = depth + 1,
                            visitedPaths = visitedPaths
                        )
                    )
```

The `getTransform()` method creates a defensive copy of the transformation matrix (line 30), which is good for encapsulation. However, the previous public `transformMatrix` field allowed direct access for reading. While the new approach is more secure, it introduces an allocation on every call. Consider documenting this behavioral change or providing a way for callers to access the transform without copying if they only need to read it (e.g., within a synchronized block).
```suggestion

    /**
     * Returns a defensive copy of the current transformation matrix.
     *
     * Note: this allocates a new [Matrix] on every call. For performance-critical,
     * read-only access that avoids allocations, use [withTransformReadLocked].
     */
    fun getTransform(): Matrix {
        synchronized(lock) {
            return Matrix(transformMatrix)
        }
    }

    /**
     * Executes [block] while holding the internal lock, providing direct read-only
     * access to the current transformation matrix without creating a copy.
     *
     * Callers must not mutate [Matrix] inside [block]. Violating this contract can
     * break invariants and thread-safety guarantees of [SelectionManager].
     */
    fun <T> withTransformReadLocked(block: (Matrix) -> T): T {
        synchronized(lock) {
            return block(transformMatrix)
        }
    }
```

The backup file cleanup strategy doesn't handle the case where backup deletion fails (line 159). If the backup file deletion fails (e.g., due to permissions or file locks), the function completes successfully but leaves orphaned backup files. Consider logging a warning if backup deletion fails, as accumulated backup files could consume significant storage over time.
```suggestion
                    if (!backupFile.delete()) {
                        Logger.e(
                            "CanvasRepository",
                            "Failed to delete backup file: ${backupFile.absolutePath}",
                            showToUser = false
                        )
                    }
